.TH "NAMED-MAKEJOURNAL" "1" "@RELEASE_DATE@" "9.21.21" "BIND 9"
.SH NAME
named-makejournal \- create a journal from zone files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.sp
\fBnamed\-makejournal\fP [\-hm] {origin} {oldfile} {newfile} [journal]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
\fBnamed\-makejournal\fP scans the contents of two zone files for
the domain specified by \fBorigin\fP, compares them, and writes the
differences into a journal file.  The resulting journal file could
then be used by \fBnamed\fP \%<#\:std-iscman-named> to load the zone and provide incremental
zone transfers.
.sp
Both \fBoldfile\fP and \fBnewfile\fP must be successfully loadable as zone
databases, and \fBnewfile\fP must have a higher SOA serial number than
\fBoldfile\fP\&.
.sp
If the optional argument \fBjournal\fP is not specified, then the journal
file name will be formed by appending the extension \fB\&.jnl\fP to the
zone file name specified as \fBoldfile\fP\&.
.sp
If the journal file already exists, then it will be applied to \fBoldfile\fP
immediately after loading. The difference between the resulting zone and
the one in \fBnewfile\fP will then be appended onto the end of the journal.
This allows creation of journal files with multiple transactions, by
running \fBnamed\-makejournal\fP multiple times, updating \fBnewfile\fP each
time.
.SH OPTIONS
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \-h
Print a usage summary.
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \-m
Enables memory usage debugging.
.UNINDENT
.SH SEE ALSO
.sp
\fBnamed(8)\fP \%<#\:std-iscman-named>, \fBnamed\-journalprint(1)\fP \%<#\:std-iscman-named-journalprint>, BIND 9 Administrator Reference Manual.
